><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC), Provisional NHS Hospital and Community Health Service (HCHS) monthly workforce statistics</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>Notes:</em></p><p> </p><ol start="1" type="1"><li>The Area of Work reproduced here is that submitted by individual NHS organisations and not subject to the types of validation procedures undertaken by HSCIC for data in official publications. As such, these figures should be treated with a degree of caution.</li><li>All figures exclude Locums.</li><li>Full time equivalent figures are rounded to the nearest whole number.</li><li>These statistics relate to the contracted positions within English NHS organisations and may include those where the person assigned to the position is temporarily absent, for example on maternity leave.</li></ol><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156609/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T16:53:34.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156609/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156609/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Hull and East Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) consultants, (b) registrars, (c) other doctors and (d) nurse practitioners were employed in accident and emergency roles by Hull and East Yorkshire Hospitals Trust in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","215329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610","Home Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>The number of staff in the Home Department employed in non frontline roles for the past 3 years is set out in Table 1. The comparative number of staff in frontline roles is also provided.<br><br>The Home Office did not collect this data prior to March 2012. In response on 25th January 2012 (column 283W) to a previous parliamentary question, an estimate was made that 20% (around 5,000) of staff in the Home Department were engaged in non-frontline roles at that time.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610/answer/previousversion/29396","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610/answer/previousversion/29396","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610/answer/previousversion/29396","Biography information for Karen Bradley","2014-11-25T14:25:30.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156610/answer","PQ 215331 Table 1 (2).xlsx","PQ 215331 Table 1 (2).xlsx","Staff in frontline roles","Staff in frontline roles","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-19","Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in her Department were employed in non-frontline roles in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","215331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156611","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-24","<p /> <p>Civil legal aid is available to help victims of human trafficking in relation to applications for leave to enter or remain in the UK, and also for claims for damages or under employment law brought by victims of human trafficking arising in connection with their exploitation. These services are set out in paragraph 32 of Schedule 1 to the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012. Victims of human trafficking are also able to apply for any other civil legal aid service for which they are eligible.</p><p> </p><p>The Legal Aid Agency does not routinely collect information on the circumstances of applicants for legal aid, except where this is directly relevant to the application. This includes whether or not applicants are victims of human trafficking, which was not relevant to any legal aid applications before the introduction of LASPO or for services other than those described under paragraph 32 of Schedule 1 to LASPO since. Data is being collected on services provided under paragraph 32, but due to the length of time it takes for cases to conclude, we do not have a clear picture of funding since implementation of LASPO. As a result, it is not possible accurately to estimate the total cost of enabling victims of human trafficking to access legal aid for the period requested.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156611/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T16:59:04.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156611/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156611/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-19","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the cost of enabling vitims of human trafficking to access legal aid in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","215330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612","Cabinet Office","false","2014-11-27","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612/answer","Reading East","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612/answer/previousversion/30260","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612/answer/previousversion/30260","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612/answer/previousversion/30260","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","2014-11-27T10:26:01.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156612/answer","PQ 411.xlsx ; PQ 215175 ONS 411.pdf","PQ 411.xlsx ; PQ 215175 ONS 411.pdf","Excel Sheet for Member - Living Wage ; ONS Letter to Member - Living Wage","Excel Sheet for Member - Living Wage ; ONS Letter to Member - Living Wage","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-11-19","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number and proportion of (a) men and (b) women in (i) full-time and (ii) part-time work in each (A) local authority area and (B) parliamentary constituency earning less than the living wage.","false","Biography information for Mr John Denham","Southampton, Itchen","Mr John Denham","215175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156613","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-24","<p>The IAEA Director General in his November report on the status of Iran’s nuclear programme reconfirmed that all of Iran’s 20% enriched uranium stockpile has been down-blended to less than 5%, or converted to oxide, in keeping with Iran’s commitments under the Joint Plan of Action.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156613/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T16:26:42.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156613/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156613/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-19","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the prospect of Iran neutralising its stockpile of 20 per cent enriched uranium.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","215336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156614","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-24","<p>We strongly condemn any suggestions from Iran’s leaders that Israel should be eliminated. We similarly strongly condemn any politically or racially motivated attempts to deny or question the Holocaust, and all anti-Semitic language.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156614/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T16:23:54.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156614/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156614/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-19","Iran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received about Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei's nine point plan for the destruction of Israel.","false","Biography information for Guto Bebb","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","215151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156615","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-26","<p>The cost of the operation has not yet been calculated in detail. However, under an existing arrangement with Department for International Development (DFID) governing military support to humanitarian assistance operations, the majority of costs incurred by the Ministry of Defence will be met by DFID.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156615/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T16:08:43.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156615/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156615/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-19","West Africa: Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of how much his Department has spent on specific steps to tackle the Ebola outbreak in West Africa to date.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","215222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156616","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-24","<p>The FCO estimates spend of approximately £106,000 since the beginning of the Ebola outbreak in West Africa. This figure forms a part of the £230 million committed by the UK Government to tackle Ebola, which includes support for 700 Ebola treatment beds in Sierra Leone, tripling current capacity. A significant area of FCO expenditure has been providing additional resilience to our Missions in the affected countries. This has helped ensure the UK is at the forefront of the international effort to tackle Ebola. A further element of spend was the UK hosted London Conference on Defeating Ebola on 2 October. The conference brought together more than 20 governments, a dozen charities and NGOs, the UN, World Bank, health experts and the private sector to pledge funds, equipment and health workers. The conference secured new pledges for Sierra Leone of over £100m and hundreds of staff for the Ebola response.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156616/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T16:08:44.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156616/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156616/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-19","West Africa: Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of how much his Department has spent on specific steps to tackle the Ebola outbreak in West Africa to date.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","215224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156617","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-26","<p>The table below shows the cost to the public purse for compensating farmers in England for TB in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total TB Compensation costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Haulage costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Salvage receipts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Net cost of TB compensation</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>£30.6m</p></td><td><p>£1.7m</p></td><td><p>-£3.4m</p></td><td><p>£28m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£28.6m</p></td><td><p>£1.8m</p></td><td><p>-£4.6m</p></td><td><p>£25.8m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£30.2m</p></td><td><p>£2.21m</p></td><td><p>-£8.9m</p></td><td><p>£23.5m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£34.1m</p></td><td><p>£2.27m</p></td><td><p>-£10.2m</p></td><td><p>£26.1m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£31.4m</p></td><td><p>£2.18m</p></td><td><p>-£8.8m</p></td><td><p>£24.8m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Defra’s costs are offset by salvage receipts. Therefore, the real cost to Defra is what is paid out in compensation and haulage, less the receipts received back for salvage.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156617/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T15:32:53.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156617/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156617/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-19","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the cost to the public purse has been of compensating farmers for TB in their herds in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","215306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156618","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-26","<p>We don’t hold information on the costs of TB to the agri-food industry. TB currently costs government around £100m per year. Additionally it is estimated to cost English livestock farmers tens of millions of pounds. The average cost to a farmer of each TB herd breakdown in the High Risk Area has been estimated at around £14,000. The average cost to a farmer of each routine TB test has been estimated at around £350.</p><p> </p><p><br></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156618/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T17:44:21.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156618/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156618/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-19","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the cost of TB in cattle herds on the UK agri-food industry in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","215307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156619","Department for International Development","false","2014-11-26","<p>Tackling the Ebola outbreak in West Africa is a top priority for my department. The UK is leading the international response in Sierra Leone and to date has committed £230 million to fight the disease.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156619/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T16:28:58.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156619/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156619/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-11-19","West Africa: Ebola","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of how much her Department has spent on specific steps to tackle the Ebola outbreak in West Africa to date.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","215223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156620","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-11-26","<p>Complaints about poor service should be directed to the communications provider who supplies the broadband service and that customers have a contractual relationship with. Openreach is not a customer-facing organisation; it was created to offer all communications providers providing retail broadband and telephone services equality of access to BT's network.</p><p>Openreach is accountable to communications providers to meet its responsibilities to manage the local access network infrastructure that connects customers to their local telephone exchange. Communications providers have a duty of care to manage consumer complaints and ensure that Openreach provides a high quality service.</p><p>Customers who are dissatisfied with the handling of their complaint by communications providers have the option of an alternative dispute resolution (ADR) scheme. An ADR Scheme is an independent system of redress for customers who feel they have been poorly or unreasonably dealt with by a communications service provider. Ofcom, the independent telecommunications regulator, requires all communications providers to be a member of such a scheme.</p><p>Since 1 July Ofcom has applied new rules to bring about faster line repairs and installations for telephone and broadband customers. As a minimum Openreach must, over the course of a given year:</p><p>• Complete 80% of fault repairs within one to two working days of being notified, irrespective of factors such as severe weather conditions.</p><p>• Provide an appointment for 80% of new line installations within 12 working days of being notified, irrespective of factors such as severe weather conditions.</p><p>• Ensure it adheres to these new standards across the country.</p><p>• Provide data on repairs and installations that are not completed within this timeframe. This information will allow Ofcom to monitor Openreach’s performance closely and intervene further if required, as this includes the ability to impose fines if necessary.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156620/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T16:56:16.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156620/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156620/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-11-19","Broadband: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what access arrangements are in place for broadband subscribers to make complaints via Openreach about poor quality of service.","false","Biography information for Dame Angela Watkinson","Hornchurch and Upminster","Dame Angela Watkinson","215154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156621","Home Office","false","2014-11-24","<p>Businesses required to comply with the transparency in supply chains provision, now included in the Modern Slavery Bill, will be required to publish their annual slavery and trafficking statement on their website. They must also include a link to the slavery and human trafficking statement in a prominent place on their website’s homepage. <br><br>Where a business uncovers slavery or trafficking in their supply chains they will be encouraged to report their concerns or findings to the relevant authorities in that jurisdiction. The statutory guidance to support businesses <br>in understanding what kinds of information they may wish to include in any slavery and trafficking statement may include guidance on reporting concerns.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156621/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T15:16:10.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156621/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156621/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-11-19","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, by what process she plans that businesses will report exploitation in their supply chains as a result of the Modern Slavery Bill.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","215322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156622","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-11-24","<p>The criteria against which planning appeals will be considered for recovery for determination by the Secretary of State are set out in the Planning Practice Guidance at: <a href="http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/guidance/appeals/planning-appeals-general/" target="_blank">http://planningguidance.planningportal.gov.uk/blog/guidance/appeals/planning-appeals-general/</a>. Careful consideration will be given to any request for recovery that is submitted.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156622/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T15:52:58.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156622/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156622/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-11-19","Planning Permission: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, under what criteria and procedures an hon. Member can seek reference to the Secretary of State of a planning application that has been rejected by a planning authority.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","215239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156623","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-11-24","<p>Shropshire Council submitted its Site Allocations and Management of Development Plan Document to the Secretary of State for examination on 1 August 2014, and its assertion that it has a five year supply of deliverable land will be robustly tested by the Planning Inspector. <br><br>Getting an up-to-date Local Plan in place, following extensive engagement with local communities and which includes a five year supply of housing sites, is the best way to protect an area from unplanned development whilst meeting local housing needs.</p><p> </p><p>Where authorities are in the process of preparing plans, they still need to demonstrate that they have in place a five year supply of deliverable housing sites. Weight can be given to policies in emerging Local Plans to the extent that they reflect policies in the National Planning Policy Framework.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156623/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T15:50:47.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156623/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156623/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-11-19","Housing: Shropshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information he holds on when Shropshire unitary authority will be in a position to bank an agreed five year land supply.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","215240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156624","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-11-25","<p>I take full account of these factors when making such decisions. At EU level the European Commission has published proposals for interim bass management measures to apply to both commercial fishing and recreational angling sectors in 2015. When these measures are agreed in December the UK will seek a more balanced approach than proposed, which more closely reflects the relative levels of mortality on bass stocks incurred by each sector, while contributing to the aim of stock recovery on a more proportionate basis.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156624/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T16:05:51.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156624/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156624/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-11-19","White Fish: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what account she takes when deciding on measures to reduce the mortality in bass stocks of the (a) value to the UK economy and the economies of other member states of recreational angling compared to commercial fishing, (b) mortality of bass stocks caused by recreational anglers compared to that caused by commercial fishing and (c) tax receipts from recreational angling compared to those from commercial fisheries.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","215206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156625","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-26","<p>Statistics on the number of additional rate income tax payers liable to pay by government office regions, including North East England, are published in HMRC’s income tax statistics, table 2.2: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/306856/Table_2.2.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/306856/Table_2.2.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Constituency level information on additional rate tax payers is not published.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156625/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T16:25:40.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156625/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156625/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-19","Income Tax: Tynemouth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people in Tynemouth constituency paid the top rate of income tax in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","215256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156626","Department of Health","false","2014-11-26","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156626/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T12:31:26.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156626/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156626/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Swinfenhall Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many prisoners held in HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Swinfen Hall have been diagnosed with (a) ADHD and (b) Asperger's Syndrome.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","215255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156627","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-11-26","<p>The number of households subject to the benefit cap by Parliamentary Constituency is published on gov.uk each quarter. The latest data, showing the total number of households capped from 15 April 2013, when the benefit cap was introduced, to August 2014, can be found in Table 1 of the data tables published here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-cap-number-of-households-capped-to-august-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/benefit-cap-number-of-households-capped-to-august-2014</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The benefit cap applies to the combined income from a number of benefits, including Income Support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>• the main out-of-work benefits (Jobseeker’s Allowance, Income Support, and Employment and Support Allowance except when the Support Component is in payment);</p><p> </p><p>• Housing Benefit;</p><p> </p><p>• Child Benefit;</p><p> </p><p>• Child Tax Credit;</p><p> </p><p>• other benefits such as Carer’s Allowance.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, the cap is currently administered through Housing Benefit. This means that, if affected, it is only a household’s Housing Benefit entitlement that is reduced so that the total amount of benefit received is no longer higher than the cap level.</p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156627/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T12:50:39.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156627/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156627/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-11-19","Income Support: Tynemouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in Tynemouth constituency have had income support capped since the introduction of the benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","215254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156628","Attorney General","false","2014-11-26","<p>Any private individual or entity who/which is not acting on behalf of the police or another prosecuting authority may bring a private prosecution. There are some organisations that regularly prosecute cases as a private prosecutor before the courts of England and Wales, for example the RSPCA. Furthermore, there are other prosecution authorities that bring prosecutions pursuant to statute, including the Serious Fraud Office and the Service Prosecuting Authority. Some offences can only be brought if the consent of the Director of Public Prosecutions or the Attorney General is obtained.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156628/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T16:22:51.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156628/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156628/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-11-19","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what bodies can prosecute without the approval of the Crown Prosecution Service.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","215172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156629","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-11-24","<p>The Government has publicly committed to introducing the zero carbon standard for new homes in 2016. This commitment was informed by a range of representations, most recently to the consultation “Next steps to Zero Carbon – Allowable Solutions” published in August 2013. The consultation and summary of responses to that consultation can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/next-steps-to-zero-carbon-homes-allowable-solutions.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156629/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T17:23:00.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156629/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156629/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-11-19","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations his Department has received on the timing of the introduction of the carbon compliance element of the zero carbon standard for new homes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Stunell","Hazel Grove","Sir Andrew Stunell","215227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156630","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-11-24","<p>The Government will publish an impact assessment to accompany its proposals for the carbon compliance element of the 2016 zero carbon home standard for new homes in due course. This will be based on further research and evidence exploring the practicalities, costs and benefits of the Government’s approach. This will also consider existing evidence, including that from the AIMC4 project in which a consortium of major house builders with the support of Innovate UK has undertaken work with the aim of pioneering the volume production of homes built to level 4 energy standards of the Code for Sustainable Homes.</p>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156630/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T17:28:20.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156630/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156630/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-11-19","Housing: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish the evidence he has received on the practicality of introducing the carbon compliance element of the zero carbon standard for new homes in 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Stunell","Hazel Grove","Sir Andrew Stunell","215228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156631","Department of Health","false","2014-11-26","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has recommended a number of treatments for rarer cancers. In addition, a number of drugs used in rarer cancers are available through the Cancer Drugs Fund administered by NHS England.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156631/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-26T17:00:05.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156631/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156631/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the extent of access on the NHS to new treatments for patients with rarer cancers.","false","Biography information for Mike Weatherley","Hove","Mike Weatherley","215320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156632","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-28","<p>A number of reforms have or are being made to strengthen the effectiveness of regulation of claims management companies (CMCs). These include a ban on CMCs offering financial rewards or similar benefits to potential claimants as an inducement to make a claim; the publication of CMCs under investigation and subject to enforcement action; key changes to the conduct rules to ensure that claims are substantiated before being pursued and any data received through telemarketing is legally obtained; the appointment of the first two independent non-executive board members to the executive-led Claims Management Regulation Board to provide a greater element of external challenge; expanding the Regulator’s enforcement tools with a new power to impose financial penalties for conduct breaches; and bringing consumer complaints against CMCs within the remit of the Legal Ombudsman. The Government is committed to improving the ability to root out and punish bad practices by CMCs, better protect the consumers who use their services or are subjected to their marketing practices; and to help organisations that are on the receiving end of high volumes of unsubstantiated claims.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156632/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-28T15:58:12.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156632/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156632/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-19","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will take steps to more effectively regulate claims management companies.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ward","Bradford East","Mr David Ward","215148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156633","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-24","<p>Details of Ministerial Meetings with External Organisations are routinely published as part of our Quarterly Transparency Return and can be obtained via our official report:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministers-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings.</p><p>The data from May 2010 to 31 March 2014 is published there. That from 1 April 2014 will be published in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156633/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T17:47:40.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156633/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156633/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-19","Qatar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will list all meetings between Ministers in his Department and representatives of Qatari defence companies in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","215271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156634","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-24","<p>Information on arms exports is published in the Annual and Quarterly Reports on Strategic Export Controls. These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences. They are available to view at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.exportcontroldb.bis.gov.uk/sdb/fox/sdb/SDBHOME" target="_blank">https://www.exportcontroldb.bis.gov.uk/sdb/fox/sdb/SDBHOME</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Bespoke reports can also be produced on specific countries and goods types, but you will need to register to download the data.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Currently the database includes information up to 30 June 2014. Information covering</p><p> </p><p>1 July to 30 September 2014 will be published in January 2015 and information covering</p><p> </p><p>1 October to 312014 will be December will be published in April 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","215273 ; 215274 ; 215275","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156634/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T15:39:32.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156634/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156634/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-19","Exports: Qatar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will list all open individual export licences with Qatar in force in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","215272"
