"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156822","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-24","<p>There is currently no requirement to declare a disability when making a claim to the employment tribunal. Therefore I am unable to answer this question.</p><p> </p><p>There were 87,200 employment tribunal claims by women in 2012 and 75,700 in 2013. In 2012 there were 22,139 claims which included a redundancy jurisdiction and in 2013 there were 15,927. <sup>(1) </sup></p><p> </p><p>It cannot be right that hardworking taxpayers should pick up the bill for employment disputes in tribunals. It is reasonable to expect people to pay towards the £74m bill taxpayers' face for providing the service. But it is important to emphasise that the Government has been very careful in ensuring that those who have limited means have fee waivers and are not excluded from seeking redress in tribunals.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice publishes, annually and quarterly, statistical data on workload trends in employment tribunals, including jurisdictional breakdowns. The most recent Tribunal Statistics quarterly tables are available at the following address: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/352915/tribunal-statistics-tables-apr-june-2014.xls.</p><p> </p><p><sup>(1) </sup>Redundancy claims can be claims for Redundancy Pay or Redundancy failure to inform and consult.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","215287 ; 215288","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156822/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T17:50:43.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156822/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156822/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-19","Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the change in the number of employment tribunal claims for redundancy  was between 2012 and 2013.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","215289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156823","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-28","<p>The estimated cost to the taxpayer, to the end of March 2016, of raising regulated national rail fares by the retail price index (RPI) in January 2015 is £39m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The estimated cost to the taxpayer, to the end of March 2016, of raising Transport for London rail fares by the retail price index (RPI) in January 2015 is £43m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The estimated cost to the taxpayer, to the end of March 2016, of removing operators’ flexibility to vary regulated fare levels within the basket of fares in January 2015 is £14m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Danny Alexander",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156823/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-28T14:09:27.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156823/answer","Biography information for Danny Alexander","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156823/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-19","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 4 November 2014 to Question 213271, what the estimated cost to the Exchequer in the calendar year 2015 will be of (a) raising regulated national rail fares by the retail price index (RPI), (b) raising Transport for London rail fares by RPI and (c) removing train operators' flexibility to vary regulated fare levels within the basket of fares.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","215333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156824","Department for Transport","false","2014-11-24","<p>The Severn River Crossings concession is expected to end in 2018. At the end of the concession, the Severn Crossings will revert to public ownership.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156824/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T16:31:58.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156824/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156824/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-11-19","Severn River Crossing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the Severn bridges to return to public ownership.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","215335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156825","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-11-24","<p /> <p>The proceeding types recorded on the Legal Aid Agency IT systems can be found in the documents “Civil Representation Guidance on Proceeding Codes: Proceedings Codes and Standard Wordings for post-April 2013 Certificates” and “Guidance for reporting Controlled Work &amp; Controlled Work matters” which can be found on gov.uk website at the following links:</p><p> </p><p>Civil Representation Guidance on Proceeding Codes: Proceedings Codes and Standard Wordings for post-April 2013 Certificates:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/345608/legal-aid-proceeding-codes-guide-april-2013.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/345608/legal-aid-proceeding-codes-guide-april-2013.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for reporting Controlled Work &amp; Controlled Work matters:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/339468/guidance-for-reporting-controlled-work-matters.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/339468/guidance-for-reporting-controlled-work-matters.pdf</a></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156825/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T17:09:35.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156825/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156825/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-11-19","Legal Aid Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which proceeding types are recorded on the Legal Aid Agency's IT systems for recording applications for civil legal aid.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","215212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156826","HM Treasury","false","2014-11-25","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Ombudsman Service (FOS) who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This question has been passed on to the FOS. The FOS will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","214895","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156826/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T11:57:57.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156826/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156826/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2014-11-19","Financial Ombudsman Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what guidance has been issued on the qualifications required to become an ombudsman in the Financial Ombudsman Service.","false","Biography information for Lord Robathan","South Leicestershire","Mr Andrew Robathan","215218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156827","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-11-25","<p>With the exception of those relating to Shaker Aamer, the British Government receives no specific assurances from the US administration about the treatment of prisoners at Guantanamo Bay, as no British nationals remain among them. However, whilst Shaker Aamer is not a British national, his connections to the UK mean that he remains a high priority for the British Government. We continue to seek assurances regarding Mr Aamer’s health and welfare through our engagement with the US authorities, and we continue to make clear to the US that we want him released and returned to the UK as a matter of urgency.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156827/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T14:43:57.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156827/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156827/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-11-19","Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assurances he has had from the US administration about the (a) treatment of remaining prisoners at Guantánamo Bay and (b) efforts to seek the release of Shaker Aamer.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","215169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156995","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Government continues to improve the health services available to veterans, investing over £22 million in providing enhanced mental health and prosthetic services. This includes the provision of nine prosthetic centres for veterans who have lost a limb as a result of their service, ten veterans’ mental health teams, a 24 hour helpline, an online counselling service and the funding of specialist post-traumatic stress disorder services through Combat Stress.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department and NHS England have increased communications with general practiontioners and others in the National Health Service, to highlight the health needs of veterans and the wider Armed Forces community.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156995/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T14:38:55.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156995/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156995/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Health Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken to check on the health of service personnel who were wounded or hurt in the Second World War and subsequent conflicts.","false","Biography information for Bob Stewart","Beckenham","Bob Stewart","906241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165802","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>There are over 1,000 more general practitioners (GPs) working and in training from the position in September 2010, the most recent figures after the General Election.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Health Education England (HEE) is reviewing the GP recruitment process and developing a pre-GP year to give exposure and experience to prospective GP applicants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HEE is also developing a returner and refresher scheme for GPs who want to re-enter the workforce.</p><p> </p>","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Daniel Poulter",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165802/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T15:43:56.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165802/answer","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165802/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to improve recruitment of GPs.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","906242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165803","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>One year on from the Government’s formal response to the Francis Report on the failings of care at Mid Staffs, this Government has taken significant strides to improve and measure patient experience and compassionate care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We have introduced a series of measures to increase the safety, transparency and accountability of the National Health Service – including a rigorous and independent new inspection regime for hospitals and a robust special measures regime to turn around any failing trusts.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>4.3 million people have completed the Friends &amp; Family Test, with feedback used locally to improve care.</p>","South West Surrey","Mr Jeremy Hunt",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165803/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T17:14:45.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165803/answer","Biography information for Mr Jeremy Hunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165803/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","NHS: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken to measure and improve patient experience and compassionate care.","false","Biography information for Alec Shelbrooke","Elmet and Rothwell","Alec Shelbrooke","906232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165804","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>We are exploring whether and how the United Kingdom might participate in the World Health Organization’s (WHO) global prevalence study on foetal alcohol spectrum disorder, which is just starting.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As this consideration is at an early stage we cannot, for example, make any commitment now on funding. We will work with the WHO and UK experts to consider how the UK could best support the WHO work.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165804/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T16:22:15.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165804/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165804/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Foetal Alcohol Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will commission a prevalence study on foetal alcohol spectrum disorder.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","906236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165805","Department of Health","false","2014-11-25","<p>The recent NHS England <em>CAMHS Tier 4 Report</em> and Health Committee report on child and adolescent mental health found variation in services. The Taskforce on Child and Adolescent Mental Health and Wellbeing is considering ways to improve access and ensure services are more responsive to children and young people’s needs.</p><p> </p>","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165805/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T17:13:58.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165805/answer","Biography information for Norman Lamb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165805/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of child and adolescent mental health services.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","906235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806","Department of Health","false","2014-11-26","<p>We are providing an additional £700 million to help the National Health Service cope with winter pressures.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Further, the Prime Minister’s £50 million Challenge Fund is currently improving general practitioner access for over 3 million patients across England. This includes offering evening and weekend appointments, as well as better use of technology. By January, 7.5 million patients will be covered.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806/answer","Battersea","Battersea","Jane Ellison","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806/answer/previousversion/30058","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806/answer/previousversion/30058","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806/answer/previousversion/30058","Biography information for Jane Ellison","2014-11-26T12:16:32.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/165806/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-11-19","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to reduce the number of patients attending A&E departments.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Roberta Blackman-Woods","906240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156150","Attorney General","false","2014-11-25","<p>Where a suspect is charged by the Crown Prosecution Service (“CPS”) with a criminal offence, there are no plans to introduce a general right of appeal relating to the offence charged on the ground that it is too lenient. There are already a number of mechanisms in place to assess the quality of prosecutors’ decision making including external reviews by Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate and internal CPS processes such as Individual Quality Assessments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Every charging decision made by the CPS must be in accordance with the Code for Crown Prosecutors (“the Code”). Unless the Threshold Test is applied, there must be sufficient evidence to provide a realistic prospect of conviction and it must be in the public interest to prosecute every offence charged. The Code requires that charges are selected which reflect the seriousness and extent of the offending, enable the case to be presented in a clear and simple way and give the courts adequate powers to sentence. The Code also makes it clear that review is a continuing process and that prosecutors must take account of any change in circumstances that develops as the case progresses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Victims can currently exercise their rights under the CPS Victims’ Right to Review scheme. This scheme enables victims to request a review of a CPS decision made after 5<sup>th</sup> June 2013 not to bring charges, to discontinue proceedings, offer no evidence or leave certain charges to “lie on file”. In those cases where it has not been possible to resolve the issue to the victim’s satisfaction at a local level, the decision is independently reviewed.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156150/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T11:43:01.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156150/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156150/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-11-18","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, if he will bring forward proposals to introduce a right of appeal against a charging decision of the Crown Prosecution Service on the grounds that it is unduly lenient.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","214940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156151","Attorney General","false","2014-11-25","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) maintains a central record of the number of prosecuted defendants, flagged as child abuse and whose principal offence was categorised as a sexual offence. These data can be further disaggregated by the gender of defendants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>During each of the last nine years, where figures are available, the number of completed prosecutions of men and women charged with sexual offences involving child abuse, is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>(a) Men</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(b) Women</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005-2006</p></td><td><p>3,441</p></td><td><p>53</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-2007</p></td><td><p>3,764</p></td><td><p>78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007-2008</p></td><td><p>3,866</p></td><td><p>74</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-2009</p></td><td><p>3,945</p></td><td><p>83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-2010</p></td><td><p>4,060</p></td><td><p>77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>4,715</p></td><td><p>79</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>4,571</p></td><td><p>82</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>3,987</p></td><td><p>60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>4,300</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data Source: CPS Management Information System – Data for 2004-2005 is not collated centrally and could only be provided at a disproportionate cost</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156151/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T11:41:28.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156151/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156151/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-11-18","Offences against Children: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many (a) men and (b) women were prosecuted for offences covering sexual activity with a child in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","215015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-24","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Small businesses are vital to our economy and our small business owners have driven this economic recovery. The Inverclyde constituency has benefitted from a number of support schemes. The Business Bank’s Start-Up Loan programme has already provided 16 loans, with a value of £55,000, to people starting a business in Inverclyde. And since May 2010, the Enterprise Finance Guarantee Scheme has supported loans in the area with a total value of £970,000.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>We are committed to making Britain the best place in the world to start and grow a business, and are doing this in a number of ways:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>£10 billion of financing will be unlocked for smaller business over the next 5 years by our British Business Bank;</li><li>Government grants of up to £3,000 for better internet connectivity are available to small businesses;</li><li>The Business Support Helpline is available to provide bespoke information and advice;</li><li>Cuts to corporation tax from 28% to 21%; and</li><li>£2,000 cut from the National Insurance bills of small firms from the new Employment Allowance.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152/answer","West Suffolk","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152/answer/previousversion/29270","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152/answer/previousversion/29270","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152/answer/previousversion/29270","Biography information for Matt Hancock","2014-11-24T15:30:34.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156152/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-18","Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what additional support he plans to give small and medium-sized businesses in the UK.","false","Biography information for Iain McKenzie","Inverclyde","Iain McKenzie","215037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156153","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive and other organisations in Northern Ireland work closely with counterparts in the British Business Bank. The Bank is engaged on the Joint Ministerial Taskforce on Banking and Access to Finance between HM Government and the Northern Ireland Executive, most recently meeting on 15 October 2014; in February 2014, Invest NI hosted a Roadshow for the British Business Bank to promote its solutions to financial intermediaries; and in September 2014, the British Business Bank presented at an event hosted by the Federation of Small Businesses in Belfast which looked at how to harness the power of SMEs in Northern Ireland. The British Business Bank will also be hosting a road show in Northern Ireland in early 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In Northern Ireland, the Business Bank works through delivery partners to deliver the Enterprise Finance Guarantee, the Investment Programme (including its predecessor Business Finance Partnership), and the Start Up Loans Programme. This activity complements the venture capital programmes run by Invest NI.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Enterprise Finance Guarantee has unlocked more than £38 million of lending in Northern Ireland since its launch in 2009. Currently, the programme supports over 130 businesses with £13 million of loans.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Investment Programme builds upon the success of the Business Finance Partnership, and is open to applications from finance providers in Northern Ireland. The combined Investment Programmes supported £2 million of lending to businesses in Northern Ireland between July and September 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The British Business Bank has signed up four Start Up Loans providers which are active in Northern Ireland and are making progress in delivering the programme. The programme has now provided Start Up Loans worth nearly £900,000 in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156153/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T13:01:01.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156153/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156153/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-18","British Business Bank: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he made of the level of the support given by (a) the Northern Ireland Assembly and (b) other organisations in Northern Ireland for the British Business Bank; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","214956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156154","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-24","<p>Since August 2012 the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has benefitted from having central records of contracts let by the Department. However, the operational management of each contract continues to rest with the respective project SRO (Senior Responsible Owner) or team, and there may often be valid reasons for any subsequent contract changes. The Department is reviewing its Commercial Strategy and expects to increase management information in this area soon but presently lacks the capacity to marry contracts let with actual payments made, and to do so would involve disproportionate cost.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156154/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-24T13:11:42.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156154/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156154/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-11-18","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether any (a) external contractors and (b) consultancy companies engaged by his Department have charged more than the initial price agreed for their services since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Evans","Islwyn","Chris Evans","214978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156155","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-11-25","<p>Eight Formal Expressions of interest in the Portsmouth Shipyard were received by the 30 June closing date of which three have been shortlisted.</p><p>Details of the specific companies are being withheld as disclosure would prejudice commercial interests</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","214842 ; 215229","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156155/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2014-11-25T17:01:35.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156155/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/156155/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-11-18","Portsmouth Dockyard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many expressions of interest in Portsmouth Shipyard have been received.","false","Biography information for Mr Mike Hancock","Portsmouth South","Mr Mike Hancock","214841"
